For a learner reading the book, this appendix is where introspection stops being read about and starts being experienced. Move the slider. See the form change. That is introspection in action, at your fingertips, in the book itself.

That interactive moment is what the Living Books doctrine (from Motoi Copilot's memory notes) is aiming at — books that are also playgrounds. This appendix is a taste.

## H.18 The round-trip guarantee, one more time

`(composer/apply c (composer/emit c))` is identity. This is the whole reason the composer is trustworthy. Every save and reload preserves state exactly. Every widget move reflects in the form. Every form edit reflects in the widgets.

Introspection over the composer is queries on both sides of the round-trip:

- `(composer/emit c)` — form-side introspection
- `(composer/widgets c)` — widget-side introspection

Together they describe the canvas fully.

