## H.23 Deep-seed — a fuller demo canvas

For a richer demo (rendered inline in Wave 4):

```scheme
(composer/canvas (:bind '(cart/synth))
  (composer/instrument-picker :bind '(cart/synth :wave) :choices '(sine square triangle saw noise))
  (composer/adsr :bind '(cart/synth :env))
  (composer/slider :label \"Cutoff\" :bind '(cart/synth :filter :cutoff) :min 20 :max 20000 :step 10 :log #t)
  (composer/slider :label \"Resonance\" :bind '(cart/synth :filter :q) :min 0 :max 1 :step 0.01)
  (composer/fx-chain :bind '(cart/synth :fx) :available '(fx/reverb fx/delay fx/distort))
  (composer/button :label \"Preview\" :emits '(synth/play cart/synth))
  (composer/live-code :bind '(cart/synth)))
```

A full synth patch editor. Seven widgets plus a live-code panel. Emit and you have a complete synth configuration as Scheme.

## H.24 Deep-seed — the composer round-trip as teaching device

For teachers: the composer-in-book is a powerful demonstration. Move the slider, see the form change. Edit the form, see the slider move. Every learner immediately understands what \"round-trip\" means.

This is often the moment where the introspection principle clicks for learners. Reading about introspection is abstract. Watching a slider mirror a form is immediate.

Wave 4 will script this teaching moment more carefully. The seed above lays down the shape.

## H.25 Deep-seed — the LLM composition

Wave 4 will show:

```scheme
;; user builds a synth patch with the composer
(define patch (composer/emit synth-canvas))

;; LLM rewrites for idiomatic style
(define improved (rewrite patch :goal 'idiomatic))

;; apply the improved form back to the canvas
(composer/apply synth-canvas improved)
;; widgets update to reflect the LLM's improvements
```

Composer + LLM composition. Every stage introspectable. Every stage a verb call.

