## H.35 Deep-seed — the interactive book vision

Motoi Copilot's design memory documents a Living Books vision — books whose pages are also live playgrounds. This appendix is a small proof of concept: a composer-in-book that shows the round-trip visually.

The vision extends further. Every chapter's code examples could be live-editable. Every value could be introspectable in place. Every macro could be expanded inline. The book becomes a workspace, not just a reference.

Wave 4 will explore how to render this book with those interactive elements when the book renderer catches up. Until then, the composer-in-book appendix is the first taste of what the interactive experience will feel like.

## H.36 Deep-seed — the reader-friendly form

For readers on static book renderers (PDF, plain text), the composer-in-book still tells a story even without interaction. Every emitted form is shown as text. Every widget change is described in prose. You can imagine the interaction and grasp the round-trip.

For readers on interactive renderers, the story becomes tangible. Move the slider yourself; see the form update in real time.

Both modes are supported. The static SLAT records above render legibly in any environment.

## H.37 Deep-seed — the composer-in-book as a training substrate

For Motoi Copilot's training corpus, this appendix contributes a specific pattern: composer widget declarations, their emitted forms, and their round-trip properties. Every code snippet is a training example of how composer verbs compose.

When Motoi Copilot generates code that uses composer verbs, the patterns from this appendix are what the model imitates.

## H.38 Deep-seed — the round-trip guarantee restated

`(composer/apply c (composer/emit c))` is identity. Save this fact. Every composer canvas satisfies it. Every implementation that fails to satisfy it is buggy.

This guarantee is what makes composer files hand-editable. Open a `.slat` composer file in a text editor, change some numbers, close the file, reopen in the composer, everything is preserved.

That editability is a design commitment. It is why the composer emits Scheme forms and not opaque binary blobs.

