## H.41 Deep-seed — a worked interactive scenario

Imagine a learner reading this appendix in an interactive renderer.

They see the demo canvas description in text. They see the four widgets rendered visually — a slider, a toggle, a color picker, a live-code panel. Below the widgets, the live-code panel shows the current form: `(demo :vol 50 :muted #f :theme 'blue)`.

They drag the slider to 75. The live-code panel updates immediately: `(demo :vol 75 :muted #f :theme 'blue)`.

They click the toggle. `(demo :vol 75 :muted #t :theme 'blue)`.

They click red in the color picker. `(demo :vol 75 :muted #t :theme 'red)`.

They edit the live-code panel directly, changing `:vol 75` to `:vol 100`. The slider moves to 100.

That is round-trip. That is introspection with a graphical dimension. The learner just experienced what fifteen chapters described.

## H.42 Deep-seed — the appendix as pedagogy

For teachers using the composer-in-book: this appendix is the moment where introspection clicks. Pause here. Give the learner time to interact. Ask them what they observe. Their observations will match every principle from Chapter 14 without you having to lecture.

The composer round-trip is the introspection lens made visible.

## H.43 A truly closing observation

The Book of Introspection is a book about invisible things — verb metadata, environments, macros, error records, Cortex records. All are queryable but none are visible until you introspect them.

The composer is the opposite. It makes the invisible visible. The form is right there in the live-code panel. The widgets are right there for you to touch. There is nothing hidden; everything is on display.

That contrast — invisible things made queryable, or visible things made queryable — is the whole introspection story from two angles.

